Iavan Pijoos, News24 (File, Netwerk24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg - The SA National Defence Union (Sandu) says the authorisation of 441 soldiers to assist police in &ldquo;law and order&rdquo; activities for the Opening of Parliament was unpresidential and indicates the political abuse of the South African National Defence Force.&nbsp;&ldquo;This is absolutely unpresidential and it shows the lack of confidence they have in the South African Police Service,&rdquo; Sandu national secretary Pikkie Greeff said. Greeff said it was "absolutely shocking" that Zuma would deploy so many soldiers.&nbsp; &ldquo;It is not an emergency situation and it should not be happening at all. It is rather shocking and inappropriate,&rdquo; he said.&nbsp; The presidency said in a statement on Tuesday evening that the SA National Defence Force members will be working in cooperation with the South African Police Service &ldquo;to maintain law and order during the Opening of Parliament where the President will deliver the State of the Nation Address 2017&rdquo;.&nbsp;The SANDF will be deployed together with the police from 5 to 10 February.&nbsp; 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.